user_data.description:
This is a quick overview of the how-to model. For a longer, in-depth explanation, see [the article page][1].

### Sheet1

`Sheet1` is the starting point for our model. It represents a simple 5-year investment. The return in each year is fixed.

### Sheet2

The first step is to change the fixed return to a randomly-distrubuted return. In `Sheet2!D3:D7` we use the _NormalValue_ function to create a random sample. If you recalculate the sheet, you will see the values change.

### Sheet3

The next step is to look at some statistics from a Monte Carlo simulation. In `Sheet3!H9:H11` we look at the _mean,_ or _average_ value for the final balance. The statistics will update every time you run a simulation.

You might notice that the mean is very close to the original, fixed value back in `Sheet1!F9:F11`, which is what we expect.

### Sheet4

To start to get a sense of the set of possible outcomes, in `Sheet4!I9:J11` we add additional statistics to see the minimum and maximum values from the simulation. This is an indication of the possible risk -- the minimum value will usually represent a net loss.

### Sheet5

The minimum and maximum values can tend to exaggerate variance, because the normal distribution is unbounded. In `Sheet5!I9:J11` we look at the 25th and 75th percentiles instead.

The 25th percentile means "during the simulation, 25% of values were this value or lower". Or put another way, "in all but the worst 25% of cases, the result was at least this amount".

[1]: https://riskamp.com/how-to
